related_questions.question: What is different about Japanese whisky?
related_questions.snippet: One of the key differences in taste between Scottish and Japanese whisky is that Japanese whisky tends to be less peated. In Scotland, where distilleries are mostly located on islands and in coastal areas, peat is naturally used for drying the barley during the malting phase.
related_questions.title: Japanese Whisky vs. Scotch: What's the difference? - Chivas Regal

related_questions.question: Does Japan have good whiskey?
related_questions.snippet: In fact, many whisky connoisseurs consider Japan to be the home of the best whiskies in the world. Despite the fact that there are significantly fewer distilleries in Japan than in Scotland, there is a truly remarkable diversity in terms of style and flavour here.

related_questions.question: Why is Japanese whisky special?
related_questions.snippet: Japanese whisky is known for its lightness and delicacy on the palate; you'll likely pick up on floral, subtle fruity notes with some woodsy depth, or sweet whispers of vanilla or honey. If you're familiar with tasting other types of whisky, then you'll have no trouble tasting your first glass of Japanese whisky.
